  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal offense in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. The specific penalties depend on the nature and extent of the crime, as outlined primarily in the **Money Laundering Control Act (18 U.S.C. \u00a7\u00a7 1956 and 1957)**. Here\u2019s an overview of the penalties:\n\n### **Criminal Penalties**\n1. **Felony Conviction**: Money laundering is a federal felony.\n2. **Imprisonment**:\n   - Under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** (transactional money laundering), a conviction can result in up to **20 years in prison**.\n   - Under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** (monetary transactions involving criminally derived property), the maximum prison sentence is **10 years**.\n3. **Fines**:\n   - Fines can be up to **$500,000 or twice the value of the property involved**, whichever is greater.\n   - For corporations, fines can be up to **$1 million or twice the value of the property involved**.\n4. **Enhanced Penalties** for Certain Cases:\n   - If the money laundering involves funds derived from drug trafficking, terrorism, or other serious crimes, penalties may be more severe, including **up to life imprisonment** in extreme cases.\n\n### **Civil Penalties**\n- Civil penalties may also be imposed, including **forfeiture of property** involved in or derived from the money laundering scheme.\n- Authorities can seize assets connected to the crime, even if no criminal charges are filed.\n\n### **Other Consequences**\n- **RICO Act Implications**: Money laundering can be prosecuted under the Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations (RICO) Act, which carries its own set of penalties, including significant prison time and asset forfeiture.\n- **Reputation and Professional Consequences**: Conviction for money laundering can result in loss of professional licenses, inability to secure future employment, and lasting damage to personal and professional reputation.\n\n### **Aggravating Factors**\nPenalties may increase if:\n- The amount of laundered money is substantial.\n- The defendant is a repeat offender.\n- The crime involves sophisticated schemes or international elements.\n\nIf you or someone you know is facing money laundering charges, it is critical to consult with a qualified federal criminal defense attorney to understand the specific implications and build a strong defense.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
